english:
  title: Another
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the twenty-seventh day of the seventh month in the second year of Zhonghe, by order of the Grand General, a feast for three hundred monks is held at Beop-un Temple in memory of the late Vice Minister of Zhao Yi. Moreover, five volumes of the Surangama Sutra and one volume of the Lotus Sutra are copied and dedicated to perpetual worship.

    It is said that the Buddha, cultivating the power of wisdom, saves all wandering sentient beings; when people awaken faith, their good vows shall be fulfilled. When we respectfully follow the teachings of the Buddha, their compassionate response shall surely come.

    The late Vice Minister possessed lofty ambitions from youth and received the weightiest trust of the sovereign. Rolling up his sleeves to train the armies, he prepared for campaign; the Emperor, cutting his robe to send urgent decrees, relied upon his miraculous strategies. We hoped to see his merit established in the thick of battle, yet suddenly calamity struck unexpectedly—Heaven has taken from us one of excellence.

    Now we humbly approach the temple gates and reverently practice the dharma. We seek out the true path in the scriptures and respectfully embrace the subtle truths of the Lotus Sutra.

    We earnestly pray: through these merit offerings, may the grievances be resolved. Though the star of disaster once shone upon the ancient land—its fate already sealed—now the sun of wisdom illuminates the path to awakening. May we establish auspicious karmic connections.

    This memorial is humbly submitted.
  footnotes:
    - Zhonghe was a reign period; this appears to be a Buddhist memorial service dedicating merit for the deceased.
    - The Lotus Sutra (Saddharmapundarika Sutra) was one of the most revered Mahayana Buddhist texts in East Asia.
    - The imagery of the 'star of disaster' and 'sun of wisdom' reflects Buddhist cosmology where celestial phenomena symbolize karmic conditions.
